<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec_reflection" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>The Law of Reflection</title>

    <corollary xml:id="vid-reflection">
	<title>Law of Reflection</title>
	<statement><p></p>
		<video youtube="zKOcySebSH0"><description>Introducing the Law of Reflection for light.</description></video>
	</statement>
  </corollary>
  <subsubsection><title>Key Ideas</title></subsubsection>

    <p>
        When a ray of light encounters an object, the light is usually <em>absorbed</em>, <em>scattered</em>, or <em>reflected</em> (or, often, some combination of all three).
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                Absorbed light will no longer move through the physical world.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Scattered light will emerge in all directions, causing the object to act as a new point source of light.  This is how you are able to see most everyday objects that do not emit their own visible light, such as a pencil or your finger. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Reflected light will move in a single new direction given by the Law of Reflection.  Objects like mirrors typically reflect most incident light.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <principle>
        <title>The Law of Reflection</title>
        <statement>
            <p></p>
          <p>For a ray of light incident on a flat mirror, the reflected angle <m>\theta_{r}</m> is equal to the incident angle <m>\theta_{i}</m>, both measured from the line normal to the surface: <me>\theta_{r} = \theta_{i}</me>
            <figure xml:id="reflection">
			<title>Reflection Figure</title>
                <caption>A diagram of the Law of Reflection.</caption>
                    <image source="optics/reflection.png" width = "90%" ><description>A transparent box sits in the center of the screen. A ray, labelled "Incident ray", hits the top of the box from the left side at an angle theta sub i and is reflected, labelled "Reflected ray", to the right side at an angle theta sub r. The Law of Reflection, theta sub i equals theta sub r, is annotated on the image.</description></image>
            </figure>
        </p>
        </statement>
    </principle>

    <subsubsection>
        <title>Activities</title>
        <activity>
            <title>Analogies for Reflection of Light</title>
            <p></p>
            <p>
               Are there any other objects in your personal experience that <q>reflect</q> or <q>bounce</q> in a way that reminds you of how light behaves?  Choose one and briefly discuss any similarities or differences you see between the two situations.
            </p>
        </activity>
    </subsubsection>
</section>